 I don't think that in all my years on earth I had ever seen that level of smugness by any party on election day. As I watched news reports and pundit panels and discussions, the liberals were exhibiting what I might describe as a "rancid effervescence." At the polls, especially in liberal bastions in New England and on the Left Coast, Clinton supporters in line to vote were already in celebratory moods and they were almost giddy talking to one another about what the night would bring. They congregated together yelling slogans and carrying placards and wearing t-shirts dissing Trump and praising Clinton. Many of them planned celebrations or were invited to liberal sponsored parties where they would celebrate Hillary Clinton's election. ...

Some had life sized cutouts of her that they could pose with--labeled "MADAME PRESIDENT." Those rare ones that work rushed home from their jobs and planted their carcasses in front of their televisions and computer screens, hardly able to contain their excitement. As the polls began to close, they ordered in pizza or other eats and no small number had stopped in the afternoon or earlier to purchase alcoholic beverages to celebrate with. As the first results began to trickle in, liberals in front of television sets, and members of the lamestream media were almost rapturous. The earliest results seemed to be indicating that the numbers were favoring Clinton

 On the sets of the liberal media, jubilant smiles were evident and they were almost tripping over their own words when they announced that with (just) 2 percent of the vote reporting from Florida, Hillary Clinton had taken an early substantial lead. Sure, some swing states were reporting Trump in the lead, but it was still early and they assumed the voting in urban areas would take care of any early Trump positives. By 9 P.M. they were still unable (or unwilling) to see the first hints that all might not be going so well. 

But by 10 P.M., there was a noticeable change in their facial expressions and their rancid effervescence no longer seemed to be bubbling on the surface. As states like Florida, North Carolina and Iowa were called for Trump, a twisted worry stole across their faces. And then when Michigan, Wisconsin, and Pennsylvania turned in Trump's favor, we began to see their stone faces with tears falling from their eyes in profusion. 

The petrified faces of liberals all across the fruited plain seemed almost to emanate the kind of smoke that comes from a fresh, warm dog t~u~r~d on a frosty morn. And as it became more and more obvious that this would not be the coronation that Hillary Clinton anticipated, even the rabid liberals began to acknowledge what was to them unthinkable. Television commentators reluctantly noted that the mood at democratic headquarters had become "subdued" and that the crowd was quickly thinning. In liberal households liberal fists pounded on liberal coffee tables all across the nation--accompanied by banal howls of NO! NO! NOOOOOOOOOOOOO!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

You know, it's fascinating how Donald Trump was actually the underdog in this entire election and primary cycle. When he first announced his candidacy, everyone scoffed at him. Nobody thought he had a chance. Then the polls came out and he was crushing all 15 other Republicans. There were still skeptics claiming that you can't trust the polls. I remember people were saying that Clinton or Sanders would have easily stomped Trump. That, it would be an easy victory. Then the primaries happened and Trump was decimating the competition. As candidates started dropping like flies, there were Democrats and Republicans who were vying for a brokered convention so Paul Ryan or John Kasich would be the candidate. And then, Kasich and Cruz dropped out. And thus, Trump was the nominee. The Republican party was so divided, with such a divisive candidate. The Democrats were also divided with another divisive candidate. It appeared that Trump was starting to run his campaign into the ground. His comments about the Muslim veteran, Mike Pence speaking out of his ass making Trump look bad, etc. And then, the audio of his "locker room talk" released. That's when everybody counted him out. Clinton was ahead of him in nearly every poll. Some of his supporters were turning against him. They brought it up nonstop in the debates. At this point, the entire media seemed to be against Donald Trump. Every news source was running smear articles on him. Seth Myers, Trevor Noah, and Stephen Colbert incessantly took shits on him. Celebrities like Katy Perry, LeBron James, and Beyonce all endorsed Clinton. FiveThirtyEight said that Hillary had a 70% chance of winning. Nobody thought Trump would win. We were all expecting to finally have our first female president. And then election night happened, and Donald Trump proved all of his naysayers wrong. As ballots started pouring in, his chances drastically went up. Then it happened: PRESIDENT TRUMP! He shocked the world! He did the impossible! And look, I was as much a Trump skeptic as anyone else. I was rooting for Clinton on this one, but when he won not only was I shocked, but I was genuinely impressed and surprisingly proud. Donald Trump is a gift to democracy, and although he didn't win the popular vote, he still represents Democracy at its purest essence. That a billionarie celebrity without any political knowledge has swept the nation and democratically achieved what everyone told him was impossible. No matter what your political rhetoric is, that's a truly incredible underdog story

tl;dr: Nobody wanted Trump to succeed, and he proved everybody wrong. Hate him or love him, you cannot deny that it's a fantastic story.

Had I been old enough to vote in this election, Clinton would have gotten my support.  I don't identify with a particular party, but rather with  individual ideas.  Throughout this heated campaign, both Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump have said some pretty controversial things.  But what people are failing to understand is that is a natural consequence of politics.  Clinton and Trump may be two of the most skilled campaigners this country has ever seen.  They have both shown they are worthy of running the country.  
      In this speech, I was particularly surprised by Donald Trump's Presidential attitude that drastically contrasted with his campaigning attitude.  His demeanor probably caught his hardcore supporters off guard.  No, there will be no wall.  No, Hillary is not going to prison.  No, Trump is not going to deport EVERY undocumented immigrant.  Those claims are just the glitter on Trump's campaign that easily catch our eye.  
      But what CAN we expect from a Trump presidency with a Republican House, Senate and possibly Judiciary?  I don't know.  Our politicians in Washington have proven time and time again that passing game-changing legislation is near impossible.  But who knows what they'll accomplish in the coming years. 
      This is not the end of the world as many people are making it seem.  Sure, we can expect to see change of some kind.  But if Trump continues the demeanor he displayed here, I can't imagine the country plunging into chaos like it has the past few days.  
      Like I said, I did not support Donald Trump ever during this election, but despite that fact, I'm looking to future with a positive attitude eager to see what President-elect Trump can do for this great country.

Congratulations to Mr Trump on a fine speech - his delivery was dignified and respectful, he thanked people, talked about national unity, international respect, the American dream, and veterans.  This was such a pleasant change from the loud, aggressive, and occasionally abusive campaign speeches.


However, if you analyse the speech there is very little substance.  For example:
7.25 "I pledge to every citizen of our land that I will be president for all Americans" - This sounds good but says nothing.  Every president (except during the Civil War) has been a president for all Americans.
9.18 "Every single American will have the opportunity to realise his or her fullest potential." - Really? How will this happen?  Obviously not everyone can realise their fullest potential as regards employment, political office, and various other areas of life.  To state the obvious - many people have the potential to become president, but there is only one post available - therefore not everyone can achieve their fullest potential.
9.45 "We're gonna rebuild our infrastructure ...... and we will put millions of our people to work as we rebuild it." - It is not clear if Trump is intending to create new jobs, or if he intends to use the currently employed labour force.

There is one measurable pledge in this speech: - 10.49 "We will double our growth and have the strongest economy anywhere in the world".  Unfortunately, Mr Trump does not indicate when he intends this to happen.  Is the starting point for growth to be measured at his inauguration?  Is the doubling to be every year or after 4 years?

On the campaign trail Mr Trump (just like all politicians!) made promises designed to appeal to his audiences - it will be interesting to see how many of these will be carried out when he becomes president.


On a somewhat flippant note: - 6.40 "Hillary has worked very long and very hard over a long period of time and we owe her a major debt of gratitude for her service to our country".  The cynical part of me thinks that by "service to our country" Trump means being a controversial and flawed candidate who has failed to defeat him.


(p.s. - does anyone know if or when Hillary made or intends to make a public speech conceding defeat?  Her concession by phone was around 4 hours ago as I write this.)
